<HEADLINE>
<P>
TUNNEL FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On behalf of Caltrans, District 7 -- and especially the bridge, construction, 
maintenance and traffic forces -- I want to express our thanks to the motoring 
public who helped us deal with the closing of the downtown Hollywood Freeway 
(101) due to last month's fire, which destroyed a portion of the RTD Metro Rail 
tunnel. 
</P>
<P>
I realize the inconvenience to commuters was horrendous. 
</P>
<P>
However, California drivers have proven once again that when we ask for their 
help, they are more than willing to respond. 
</P>
<P>
While the various freeway closures were in place, Caltrans' maintenance forces 
removed graffiti from signs and walls, replaced some signs and washed the rest. 
They also replaced 4,200 pavement markers; stenciled pavement markings on all 
closed ramps; repaired guardrails and one bridge joint; swept shoulder areas, 
as well as maintained closures and barricades at all approaches to the downtown 
101 slot. 
</P>
<P>
When Caltrans and the California Highway Patrol began reopening freeway 
sections and ramps, it was very gratifying to see motorists smile and give us 
the thumbs-up sign as they drove by. I also want to thank the Los Angeles City 
Department of Transportation and County Health; RTD/Los Angeles County 
Transportation Commission/Metro Rail; the fire companies from throughout the 
Southland; the Los Angeles police and CHP, Cal/OSHA; Tutor-Salib-Perini, Metro 
Rail contractor and the Red Cross. 
</P>
<P>
JERRY B. BAXTER 
</P>
<P>
District 7 Director, Caltrans 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Firefighters at the tunnel blaze. Los Angeles Times 
</P>
