<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Is That U?Irish singer Sinead O'Connor, who started a controversy when she 
refused to let the U.S. national anthem be played before a recent concert, 
donned a wig and duped protesters and a television reporter at a Wednesday 
night performance in Saratoga Springs, N.Y. O'Connor, whose hair is closely 
cropped, wore a brown shoulder-length wig and baseball cap as she sat outside 
the gates of the Saratoga Performing Arts Center before the show. O'Connor 
mingled for nearly an hour as a half-dozen demonstrators asked her fans to 
boycott her performance. At one point, a television reporter for WNYT in 
Albany, who did not recognize O'Connor, interviewed her for a reaction story. 
BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
