GI CLEARED IN PANAMA SLAYING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
FORT BRAGG, N.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A military jury today acquitted a veteran paratrooper on charges that he 
unnecessarily killed a Panamanian during the 1989 invasion of the country. 
</P>
<P>
The jurors deliberated nearly two hours before clearing Master Sgt. Roberto 
Bryan. The verdict was greeted by applause from other soldiers in the 
courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
Bryan sighed with relief. 
</P>
<P>
Bryan, a 19-year Army veteran and member of Ft. Bragg's 82nd Airborne Division, 
was charged with unpremeditated murder. A conviction would have carried a 
sentence of life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
The Army had said Bryan, 42, shot a Panamanian with his M-16 rifle without 
provocation during the invasion. 
